"    Progression of E coli O157:H7 infections in children",
"   </div>",
"   <div class=\"cntnt\" style=\"width: 499px; height: 309px; background-image: url(data:image/gif;base64,);\">",
"   </div>",
"   <div class=\"lgnd\">",
"    About 3 days after ingestion of the organism, the patient develops diarrhea, abdominal pain, fever, and vomiting. The diarrhea becomes bloody 1 to 3 days later, rarely on the first day. In 80 to 90 percent of infected children with positive cultures, visible blood is present in the stools. When bloody diarrhea first develops, the patient has a normal platelet count, creatinine concentration, and packed-cell volume, with no red-cell fragmentation. However, if studies of the coagulation and fibrinolytic systems are done early in the illness, there is evidence that thrombin generation is increased, fibrin deposition is occurring, and plasminogen activation is suppressed.",
"    <div class=\"footnotes\">",
